This chapter will cover different types of Property insurance policies for Personal Lines. You will begin by studying the Dwelling and Homeowners policies. You will also learn about different other types of property coverages, such as flood and personal watercraft, among others.

Terms to Know
Abandonment — the relinquishing of insured property into the hands of another, or into the possession of no one in particular
Appurtenant structures — buildings or structures located on the same premises as the main insured building (e.g., detached garage, shed, gazebo)
Boarder — a person who lives with someone else for an agreed upon price, usually for a considerable amount of time
Counterfeit — fraudulent imitation, forgery
Debris — remains of anything broken down or destroyed
Incidental — something occurring as a minor accompaniment to something else
Incidental occupancy — minor uses that are accessory to or support the predominant occupancy (e.g., a piano teacher giving lessons in her home)
Ordinance — a law that must be complied with
Overinsurance — when a property's insurance coverage exceeds its cash value
Vandalism — intentional destruction or damage to property

Dwelling Policies
The dwelling property policy was developed by the ISO to be used primarily as a property coverage form. The policy can be used to insure the dwelling only, contents only, or both. There are 3 separate coverage forms available under the dwelling program: basic, broad, and special form coverage. Endorsements exist to amend the coverage to tailor it to the specific needs of the policy applicant. Liability coverage is not included, but can be added. In practice, this is a common policy form used to insure rental dwellings.

Note: ISO classifies dwelling property policies as DP with a corresponding form number to denote the policy type (DP-1, DP-2, or DP-3).

A Dwelling Property policy can be purchased to insure properties solely used for residential purposes in the following situations:

Up to 5 roomers or boarders;
Up to 4 residential units;
Properties in the course of construction;
Owner occupied, tenant occupied or both;
Mobile homes on the basic form only, if they contain no more than one apartment, and are located at a permanent location listed in the policy;
Seasonal dwellings unoccupied for 3 or more months during a 12-month period; or
Not designed as farm property.
Business occupancies may impact eligibility under the dwelling property program. Business occupancies can be accommodated as long as they are incidental, are conducted by the insured on the dwelling premises, and if there are no more than 2 persons working at any time. Permissible incidental occupancies include small service operations where sales of merchandise are not the primary function, for example, barber and beauty shops, tailors, or shoe repair operations that use handwork only. Professional offices, private schools or studios such as music or photography may also be considered.

1. Coverage Forms
The 3 coverage forms applicable to the dwelling property policy define the coverages, perils or causes of loss insured against, other coverages, exclusions and conditions. Every ISO form has a certain flow to the information. The DP form structure is as follows: 

Agreement — insuring agreement (states that the insurer will provide coverage described in the policy in return for the premium paid and compliance with all applicable policy provisions);
Definitions — limited in nature;
Deductible — applies to all covered losses unless noted otherwise in the policy form;
Coverages, including Other Coverages — define direct and indirect property coverages, and additional coverages included in the premium charge;
Perils Insured Against — vary by form and is a key differentiator in form selection;
General Exclusions — perils not covered in all forms; and
Conditions — specify when coverage will apply.
The forms available in the dwelling program are as follows:

Form Name	Form Number	Peril Type(s)
Basic	DP 00 01 or DP1	Named Peril
Broad	DP 00 02 or DP2	Named Peril
Special	DP 00 03 or DP3	Open and Named Peril
Basic
Dwelling form DP 00 01 is a named peril coverage form and provides the most limited coverage of the three forms. It is very important to understand the circumstances in which a particular peril does not apply. Unlike the broad and special forms, there is no minimum amount of insurance required for the basic form. The basic form insures against the following perils or causes of loss:

1. Fire or Lightning and Internal Explosion — An explosion that takes place in a dwelling, other structure, or in a structure containing covered personal property will be covered. Coverage does not include loss or damage resulting from electric arcing, breakage of water pipes, breakage or operation of pressure relief devices, or explosion of steam boilers or steam pipes owned, leased or operated by the insured. An example of a covered loss is an explosion of a gas stove.

Regarding the peril of fire, that to be covered, the loss must be the result of a hostile fire — a fire that was not intentional and not contained with its intended boundaries, unlike a friendly fire (such as a fireplace). If a friendly fire escapes these boundaries and causes damage to other property, the fire would then be considered a hostile fire and will be covered by the insurance policy. However, a fire does not have to originate from a friendly fire to be considered hostile.

In addition to these causes of loss, the insured can add the extended coverage perils to the basic policy for an additional premium. This coverage is printed in the basic form, but is only activated if included on the declarations page and with payment of the additional premium. The perils included in the extended coverages are listed next.

2. Windstorm or hail — Damage to the insured property from windstorm or hail is covered subject to the following limitations:

Awnings, signs, and antennas outside the dwelling are not covered.
Damage by rain, snow, sleet, sand, or dust to the interior of a building or to personal property located in the dwelling will be covered only if the wind or hail damages the roof or a wall of the building first, by which creating an opening to the interior of the building. For example, if interior damage results from wind or hail entering through an open window, there would be no coverage.
No coverage applies to rowboats and canoes (outside of the building); and
No coverage for trees, shrubs, plants or lawns.
3. Explosion — The peril of internal explosion is expanded in the extended coverage perils. The explosion does not have to occur inside the dwelling. The same limitations to coverage apply to explosions as in the internal explosion peril.

4. Riot or civil commotion;

5. Aircraft — Includes self-propelled missiles and spacecraft.

6. Vehicles — Coverage does not apply to damage caused by vehicles owned or operated by an insured or a resident of the location listed in the policy. There is also no coverage for loss or damage to fences, driveways, or walks caused by a vehicle.

7. Smoke — Sudden and accidental damage caused by smoke is covered (including the emission or puffback of smoke, soot, fumes or vapors from a furnace or boiler). Coverage does not include smoke from agricultural smudging, industrial operations, or from a fireplace (friendly fires).

8. Volcanic eruption — There is no coverage for loss caused by earthquake, land shock waves, or tremors.

There are a couple of acronyms that can be used to help remember the extended coverage perils.

WHARVES:

