If the extended coverage perils are insured on the policy, the insured also may add coverage for vandalism and malicious mischief.

9. Vandalism or malicious mischief (VMM) — covers loss or damage to property from willful and malicious destruction of the insured property. Exceptions to coverage are as follows:

Glass breakage or safety glazing material that is part of the building (except glass building blocks) is not covered by this peril. For example, a vandalized window would not be covered, but decorative glass building blocks would be covered.
Damage to the building resulting from theft or burglary is covered; however, the actual property stolen is not covered. 
There is no coverage if, preceding the loss, the insured's premises has been vacant for more than 60 consecutive days immediately before the loss occurs.
Broad
The broad form (DP 00 02 or DP-2) coverage expands the causes of loss insured under the basic form with extended coverage perils, and vandalism or malicious mischief purchased. The broad form further expands coverage for the following perils:

Breakage of glass and safety glazing material that is part of the building would be covered for vandalism. Remember, in DP-1 only glass building blocks were covered for this type of loss; and
Explosion is covered without the exceptions listed in the basic form.
The 7 additional broad form perils are described below:

1. Damage by burglars — The broad form dwelling includes burglary damage as a separate peril. DP-1 form included this coverage under vandalism or malicious mischief. Coverage is now provided for damage to any covered property (not just the building) if caused by burglary. There is no coverage for property theft, or if the dwelling has been vacant for more than 60 consecutive days immediately before the loss.

2. Falling objects — Loss or damage resulting from falling objects is covered, except damage to awnings, fences, outdoor equipment, outdoor radio and television antennas or aerials, masts, or towers. Damage to the interior of a building is covered only if the roof or an outside wall was damaged first. There is no coverage for the falling object itself.

3. Weight of ice, snow or sleet — Loss or damage to the building or contents caused by the weight of snow, ice, or sleet is covered. There is no coverage for damage to piers, wharves, docks, awnings, fences, swimming pools, foundations, retaining walls, pavement, or patios.

4. Accidental discharge or overflow of water or steam — Damage caused by the accidental discharge or leakage of water or steam from a plumbing, heating, air conditioning, or automatic sprinkler system is covered. The cost to tear out and replace a part of the building is also covered if necessary to repair or replace the appliance. Tear out coverage applies to other structures only if there is actual damage to the other structure.

However, the policy will not pay for loss or damage caused by continuous or repeated seepage over a period of weeks, months, or years. It will also not pay for the cost to repair or replace the appliance itself, nor will it consider a sump pump, roof drain, gutter, or downspout as an appliance that triggers coverage. Damage caused by discharge from an off-premises storm drain, steam, or sewer pipe is not covered. If the dwelling has been vacant for more than 60 consecutive days immediately before the loss, this peril will be excluded from coverage.

5. Sudden and accidental tearing apart, cracking, burning or bulging — The sudden and accidental tearing apart, cracking, burning, or bulging of appliances from a steam or hot water heating system, an air-conditioning system, an automatic fire protection sprinkler system, or an appliance for heating water, is covered. Loss caused by freezing is not covered, but is covered in the freezing peril noted below.

6. Freezing — The freezing of plumbing, heating, air conditioning, or automatic sprinkler systems is covered only if the insured has taken reasonable steps to maintain heat in the building or has shut off the water and drained the pipes and appliances. Items not considered appliances are not covered for freezing.

7. Sudden and accidental damage from artificially generated electrical current — There is no coverage for damage to tubes, transistors, or electronic components or circuitry that are part of appliances, fixtures, computers, and home entertainment units.

The acronym B.B. BICE-GOLF can be used to remember the broad form coverage perils:

Bursting of heating systems;
Burglary damage;
Breaking of water heaters;
Ice, snow, or sleet weight;
Collapse of building or part of a building;
Electrical damage (artificially generated);
Glass breakage;
Objects falling from outside;
Leakage of water or steam damage;
Freezing of plumbing.
In addition, the broad form also includes the following other coverages:

Lawns, trees, shrubs, and plants — Loss or damage to lawns, trees, shrubs, and plants is covered if caused by fire, lightning, explosion, riot or civil commotion, aircraft, nonowned or operated vehicles, or vandalism and malicious mischief (excluding theft). This is an additional amount of insurance and is limited to a maximum of $500 per tree, shrub, or plant, and a maximum per loss of 5% of the amount of coverage on the dwelling.

Breakage of glass — Glass or safety glazing material that is a part of the covered building, including storm doors and storm windows, is covered. Also covered is loss or damage to other covered property caused by the breakage of glass. There is no coverage for glass breakage if the building or structure has been vacant for a certain number of days (more than 60 consecutive days).

Collapse — The broad and special forms cover collapse of a building or a part of a building if the loss is the result of hidden decay, insect, or vermin (only if existence of such was unknown to the insured), weight of personal property or rain that collects on the roof, the use of defective materials or methods in construction (if the collapse occurs during construction), or one of the broad form perils. Collapse does not include settling, cracking, shrinkage, bulging, or expansion. This is not considered an additional amount of insurance.

Special
Unlike the basic and broad forms, which are named peril forms, the special form (DP 00 03 or DP-3) is an open peril form. In other words, all perils are insured against except those specifically excluded. The special form only covers the dwelling and other structures on an open peril basis. The insured's personal property is covered for the broad named perils found in the DP 00 02, with a few exceptions that will be discussed.

The primary differences between the broad form DP-2 and special form DP-3 coverages include the following:

Theft of property that is a part of the dwelling or other structure is covered in the special form.
The coverage for accidental discharge or overflow of water and steam is expanded to cover loss as the result of accidental discharge or overflow from water or steam pipes that occurs off of the insured premises.
There are no exclusions for antennas, outdoor equipment, fences, or awnings from the peril of falling objects in the special form.
The special form policy will provide coverage for damage to a roof caused by freezing or thawing of water under roof shingles (an ice dam).
